                  "BodyCopy": "\u003cp\u003eFor all their mystery, the Marfa Lights somehow make sense here. Perched nearly a mile high in the desert, the sweeping plains that stretch away from Marfa\u0026rsquo;s two main streets have long served as a stage for arts and the surreal.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eMarfa\u0026rsquo;s unlikely transformation from a sleepy ranching outpost to a desert-chic oasis for contemporary creatives began in 1971 when Donald Judd, an artist and major Minimalist, relocated from New York City. He acquired the town\u0026rsquo;s decommissioned WWII army base, filled two old artillery sheds with more than 100 pieces of art and scattered 15 giant concrete-box art installations in a lonely pasture.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eToday, Judd\u0026rsquo;s 340-acre \u003ca href=\"https://chinati.org/\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eChinati Foundation\u003c/a\u003e has inspired a slew of surreal desert-scape art installations that seem to defy logic, such as \u003ca href=\"http://www.bbc.com/travel/story/20110317-americas-strangest-roadside-attractions\" target=\"_blank\"\u003ePrada Marfa\u003c/a\u003e, a faux boutique filled with faux designer handbags and heels in front of a desolate field.\u003c/p\u003e",
