                  "BodyCopy": "\u003cp\u003eWhen Judd began converting Marfa\u0026rsquo;s abandoned buildings into galleries in the 1970s, visitors began trickling in. Yet, were it not for 92-year-old Armando Vasquez (pictured), the legend of Marfa\u0026rsquo;s mystery lights may never have spread beyond the Chinati Mountains. \u0026ldquo;The first time I saw the lights was in 1971, and I was amazed \u0026ndash; it seemed like a fairy tale,\u0026rdquo; Vasquez said. \u0026ldquo;Business [in Marfa] had been slow, and I could see the potential these lights could bring to our town.\u0026rdquo;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSo, for the next 20 years, Vasquez began taking visitors from Marfa\u0026rsquo;s two motels out to a dusty bluff at dusk to see the lights. \u0026ldquo;For years, we didn\u0026rsquo;t have anyone here except the people who wanted to see the lights,\u0026rdquo; Vasquez said. \u0026ldquo;I was afraid Marfa would turn out to be a ghost town, but this was very good because it helped to keep our town alive.\u0026rdquo;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eVasquez petitioned the Marfa Chamber of Commerce to help promote the phenomenon for years to no avail. Then in 1986, they finally organised the inaugural \u003ca href=\"http://marfachamber.org/menu/\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eMarfa Lights Festival\u003c/a\u003e. Thirty-two years later, the annual festival is still held each September, and it now attracts thousands of spectators.\u003c/p\u003e",
