                  "BodyCopy": "\u003cp\u003eOn Christmas morning, Anthony Ross woke up on an island at the point where the Gulf of Maine meets the Bay of Fundy. Outside, the wind whipped across the frozen brown grass, blowing snow in drifts against the lighthouse while waves lapped the rocky shore. In the next room, his older brother Russell was already awake and keeping a watchful eye on the sea.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIt was not exactly how one pictures a family holiday, but for the lighthouse keepers of Machias Seal Island, it would have to make do. Once the helicopter lands on this 18-acre hunk of rock between the US and Canada, there is no going home until the end of the month.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026ldquo;You are away from home for 28 days at a time; that is the hardest part. But you get used to that,\u0026rdquo; said Russell, who has been a lighthouse keeper for about 20 years.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eLuckily, Russell and Anthony came prepared with turkey, presents and beer \u0026ndash; all anyone needs for a nice Christmas day. After decorating the tree and calling their families back home in Nova Scotia, the brothers tucked into a roast dinner.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026ldquo;It was a pretty good Christmas, all around,\u0026rdquo; Russell recalled.\u003c/p\u003e",
