                  "BodyCopy": "\u003cp\u003eOften performed every Thursday for the first year after someone\u0026rsquo;s death, as well as on the 40th day after death and the one-year anniversary, the rite of \u003cem\u003ejyt chygaruu\u003c/em\u003e is done to memorialise the dead.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eTraditionally, after cooking either borsook or \u003cem\u003emai tokoch\u003c/em\u003e \u0026ndash; a larger, round fried bread made from the same dough \u0026ndash; the bread, along with sweets and cookies, are spread over the table. Then someone recites verses from the Koran. In the case of these widows, the prayer was led by a young neighbour, as custom holds that only married women or men can lead the prayer.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe rhythmic, soothing prayers name the dead, asking God to forgive their sins and protect them in the afterlife. After the prayer, the family eats. (Credit: Amanda Ruggeri)\u003c/p\u003e",
