                  "BodyCopy": "\u003cp\u003eIf you can say one thing about Tajik culture, it\u0026rsquo;s that people prioritise making time for others. Walk through a city and people are sitting on benches, chatting and relaxing. Show up at a stranger\u0026rsquo;s door and your hosts will welcome you with not only warm smiles but also a table laden with food and endless amounts of tea.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026ldquo;In many big, industrial cities in Europe, people are so busy that they have no time for sharing anything \u0026ndash; time, food or even just talking with each other,\u0026rdquo; said Munira Shahidi, a Tajik professor in Dushanbe who has lived in the UK. \u0026ldquo;They\u0026rsquo;re always running from place to place. We\u0026rsquo;re saying you can be very busy, but you should not forget to share your time and space with others.\u0026rdquo;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eNo dish is a better example of this generosity of spirit than oshi palav (pronounced \u0026lsquo;peel-OW\u0026rsquo;), often anglicised as \u0026lsquo;rice pilaf\u0026rsquo;. A slow-cooked mix of rice, vegetables and usually meat, oshi palav holds a special place in Tajik culture. It\u0026rsquo;s the main dish at celebrations and festivals, and \u0026lsquo;osh\u0026rsquo;, as it often is called, is said to bring families together, secure friendships, solve arguments \u0026ndash; and may even have helped end civil war.\u003c/p\u003e",
