                  "BodyCopy": "\u003cp\u003eIn this rocky, remote country, the poorest in Central Asia, rice is precious. \u0026ldquo;Rice is a sacred grain. In Tajik culture, there is a saying that rice is the teeth of the prophet Muhammad,\u0026rdquo; said Dilshad Rahimi, deputy head of research at Tajikistan\u0026rsquo;s Institute of Culture.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eBecause oshi palav is meant to be eaten communally, that precious rice is rarely made in small amounts. One popular recipe for making osh at home is called \u0026lsquo;one-to-one\u0026rsquo;: 1kg of rice, 1kg of carrots and 1kg of lamb. At festivals and celebrations, meanwhile, it\u0026rsquo;s not uncommon to see a cook making the dish for more than 100 people at a time, standing over a steaming pot of rice wider than he is. Some of the most skilled cooks can even make the dish for more than 500 people at once.\u003c/p\u003e",
