                  "BodyCopy": "\u003cp\u003eAs one oft-quoted saying puts it, \u0026ldquo;If there\u0026rsquo;s no osh, there\u0026rsquo;s no friendship.\u0026rdquo; Share osh, on the other hand, and you\u0026rsquo;ve laid the foundations for amity \u0026ndash; even peace.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eOsh is a key part of how Tajiks often settle disagreements. The action of exchanging osh between neighbours is interpreted to mean wanting peace with one another. And if people are arguing, it\u0026rsquo;s traditional for an elder to intervene and have the two sides work out their differences over a shared plate.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eBut the most dramatic example came during Tajikistan\u0026rsquo;s five-year civil war. In 1995, after three years of violence \u0026ndash; by the end, up to 100,000 people were killed \u0026ndash; the warring factions sat down to a plate of osh. It wasn\u0026rsquo;t a quick fix though; two more years of talks and complications followed. Even so, Tajiks often refer to the \u0026lsquo;palav of peace\u0026rsquo; as the turning point for their country.\u003c/p\u003e",
