            "AmbientVideo": "",
            "BodyCopy": "\u003cp\u003eWaterford\u0026rsquo;s two remaining blaa bakeries share a great deal in terms of their heritage and process. Both bakeries are historical, family-run and rely on only three or four bakers at a shift. But there are key differences. Walsh\u0026rsquo;s, which opened in 1921, still uses their original location \u0026ndash; just down the street from Hickey\u0026rsquo;s \u0026ndash; for baking at night. By day, though, they use a new factory on the outskirts of town, where their bakers show off top-end machinery and where a space is being set up specifically to exhibit the blaa\u0026rsquo;s history and heritage to visitors.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAt Hickey\u0026rsquo;s, meanwhile, the bakery remains in its original location in a room behind the shopfront. Technology is at a minimum, with a mixer and a rudimentary machine that helps shape the dough into balls. The slower process means the dough gets more time to sit. \u0026ldquo;It\u0026rsquo;s a bit like sourdough, you see. It\u0026rsquo;s all about leaving it to rest, knocking it back and letting it rise again,\u0026rdquo; Hickey said.\u003c/p\u003e",
